The paper deals with optimization problems in combinatorial markets, which is a topic that falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The use of pricing as a tool for optimization suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of algorithmic game theory (cs.AI). The lower bounds on welfare approximation and revenue approximation involve concepts from optimization and approximation algorithms, which could place the paper in the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The focus on valuations and allocation of goods suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of economic theory (cs.EC). Finally, the use of mathematical techniques and analysis to derive the results could place the paper in the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG).
